I do, for the record, use ChatGPT more than Claude; the biggest factor is t=
he vastly superior ChatGPT Mac app. John Gruber noted at Daring Fireball ( =
https://daringfireball.net/linked/2024/10/31/anthropic-mac-app-electron-tur=
d ) :

There=E2=80=99s much talk that Anthropic=E2=80=99s Claude 3.5 has pulled ah=
ead of OpenAI=E2=80=99s ChatGPT 4o in terms of chatbot =E2=80=9Cintelligenc=
e=E2=80=9D, but as an overall experience ChatGPT wins hands-down. For one t=
hing ChatGPT has been able to search the web for answers for a while now, a=
nd it works great. For another, just today OpenAI launched ChatGPT=E2=80=99=
s dedicated =E2=80=9Csearch=E2=80=9D mode. Claude has nothing like it.

But even their respective Mac apps are a stark contrast. The Claude app is =
a lazy Electron port. Right off the bat, the email field on the login scree=
n doesn=E2=80=99t support autofill. Once you=E2=80=99re logged in, you don=
=E2=80=99t get any standard MacOS features. And of course because it=E2=80=
=99s Electron it=E2=80=99s bloated architecturally and uses a lot of memory=
. If you really want to use Claude as an =E2=80=9Capp=E2=80=9D on your Mac =
you=E2=80=99d be better off saving a web app with Safari (File =E2=86=92 Ad=
d to Dock=E2=80=A6) than using this.

ChatGPT=E2=80=99s native Mac app, on the other hand, is a truly native Mac =
app. It looks like a Mac app and feels like a Mac app because it really is =
a Mac app. I=E2=80=99ve liked it ever since it launched back in May, and it=
 keeps getting better. And I keep using it more and more as my go-to resour=
ce for answering questions.

Look, I get that this may seem silly to some; it=E2=80=99s like preferring =
to talk to someone slightly more dumb because they have better table manner=
s and appearance. Isn=E2=80=99t the point the intelligence, and isn=E2=80=
=99t Claude better? I mean, maybe, but for me AI is a tool, and part of the=
 usefulness of a tool is its ergonomics, and ChatGPT is just flat-out bette=
r; I want to use it because it=E2=80=99s nice to use, and I can=E2=80=99t s=
ay the same for Claude. Yes, this is a very =E2=80=9Cconsumery=E2=80=9D tak=
e, but, well, this is part of how OpenAI pushes its massive lead in consume=
r mindshare!

There are more benefits to being a real Mac app than just look-and-feel; fr=
om TechCrunch ( https://techcrunch.com/2024/11/14/chatgpt-can-now-read-some=
-of-your-macs-desktop-apps/ ) :

OpenAI=E2=80=99s ChatGPT is starting to work with other apps on your comput=
er. On Thursday, the startup announced the ChatGPT desktop app for macOS ca=
n now read code in a handful of developer-focused coding apps, such as VS C=
ode, Xcode, TextEdit, Terminal, and iTerm2. That means developers will no l=
onger have to copy and paste their code into ChatGPT, which has become a co=
mmon way to use the chatbot. Now when the feature is enabled, OpenAI will a=
utomatically send the section of code you=E2=80=99re working on through its=
 chatbot as context, alongside your prompt. However, unlike popular AI codi=
ng tools such as Cursor or GitHub Copilot, ChatGPT is currently unable to w=
rite code directly into developer apps on your behalf.

The feature, called Work with Apps, is far from an AI agent, but OpenAI say=
s getting ChatGPT to understand other apps is a =E2=80=9Ckey building block=
=E2=80=9D toward building agentic systems. One of the biggest challenges fa=
cing AI agents today is getting them to understand the rest of your compute=
r screen, as opposed to prompts or their own responses. OpenAI says it=E2=
=80=99s focusing this feature on coding apps to start; this is likely becau=
se AI coding assistants have taken off as one of the most popular use cases=
 for LLMs. The feature is available to Plus and Teams users today and will =
roll out to Enterprise and Edu in the next few weeks. OpenAI says ChatGPT w=
ill be able to work with other types of apps moving forward, specifically t=
ext-based apps that could be used for writing tasks.

An electron app could use the same accessibility APIs that ChatGPT is lever=
aging to read apps, but the work would be more complex, and frankly, seems =
unlikely given the low level of effort present in the app itself. What is n=
ice for me is that the list of supported apps now includes BBEdit, which I =
use to write; now I can simply ask ChatGPT questions about something I have=
 written without any copy-and-pasting; it has the full context of the Artic=
le.

Anyhow, is the quality of the ChatGPT Mac app worth a $180/month premium to=
 Claude? Well, for most people certainly not, but it=E2=80=99s definitely w=
orth a fair bit to me! But hey, it=E2=80=99s a moot point: the Mac app isn=
=E2=80=99t a Pro feature, or even a Plus feature (although =E2=80=9CWork wi=
th Apps=E2=80=9D is); it is, however, a reason to commit to a particular mo=
del, and who knows, maybe the unlimited usage will mean I choose the ChatGP=
T $200 option instead of a similar Pro level from an alternative.

