There has been a lot of talk about the importance of scale in terms of LLM =
performance; for auto-regressive LLMs that has meant training scale. The mo=
re parameters you have, the larger the infrastructure you need, but the pay=
off is greater accuracy because the model is incorporating that much more i=
nformation. That certainly still applies to o1 , as the chart on the left i=
ndicates.

It=E2=80=99s the chart on the right that is the bigger deal: o1 gets more a=
ccurate the more time it spends on compute at inference time. This makes se=
nse intuitively given what I laid out above: the more time spent on compute=
 the more time o1 can spend spinning up multiple chains-of-thought, checkin=
g its answers, and iterating through different approaches and solutions.

Here=E2=80=99s the thing: compute is expensive, both in terms of marginal c=
osts (primarily electricity), and also in terms of opportunity costs (the G=
PUs used for thinking can=E2=80=99t be used by other paying customers, whic=
h means their depreciation costs are spread over fewer queries). This is an=
other angle to think about ChatGPT Pro pricing: if you want access to model=
s that require significantly more compute capacity, you=E2=80=99re going to=
 have to pay for it.

It=E2=80=99s also a big departure from how we have thought about LLMs to da=
te: one of the =E2=80=9Cbenefits=E2=80=9D of auto-regressive LLMs is that y=
ou=E2=80=99re only generating one answer in a serial manner. Yes, you can g=
et that answer faster with beefier hardware, but that is another way of say=
ing that the pay-off from more inference compute is getting the answer fast=
er; the accuracy of the answer is a function of the underlying model, not t=
he amount of compute brought to bear. Another way to think about it is that=
 the more important question for inference is how much memory is available;=
 the more memory there is, the larger the model, and therefore, the greater=
 amount of accuracy.

In this o1 represents a new inference paradigm: yes, you need memory to loa=
d the model, but given the same model, answer quality does improve with mor=
e compute. The way that I am thinking about it is that more compute is kind=
 of like having more branch predictors, which mean more registers, which re=
quire more cache, etc.; this isn=E2=80=99t a perfect analogy, but it is int=
eresting to think about inference compute as being a sort of dynamic memory=
 architecture for LLMs that lets them explore latent space for the best ans=
wer.

To that end, it=E2=80=99s hardly a surprise that o1 API pricing is dramatic=
ally more expensive than 4o:

1M input tokens 1M output tokens GPT-4o $5.00 $15.00 GPT-4o mini $0.15 $0.6=
0 o1-preview $15.00 $60.00 o1-mini $3.00 $12.00

This pricing probably understates the delta, given that o1 is going to use =
more tokens to generate an answer. Moreover, 4o remains the better choice f=
or a lot of use cases that don=E2=80=99t require logic, above-and-beyond be=
ing a lot cheaper.

o1-pro is only available in ChatGPT to start, so we don=E2=80=99t have API =
pricing yet, but I=E2=80=99m sure it=E2=80=99s even more expensive; it=E2=
=80=99s also slower, which makes it worse for many use cases (like most of =
mine). What is interesting, however, is that API pricing is fairly straight=
forward in terms of OpenAI=E2=80=99s costs; it=E2=80=99s basically a cost-p=
lus model. What is tricky about ChatGPT Pro pricing is that OpenAI does nee=
d to take care that its promise of ( near ( https://help.openai.com/en/arti=
cles/9824962-openai-o1-and-o1-mini-usage-limits-on-chatgpt-and-the-api ) ) =
unlimited model access fits within a single monthly price. That is a bias f=
or a higher price rather than a lower one, which is fine: o1 is highly diff=
erentiated, i.e. it has low substitutability, if you find a use for it outs=
ide of solving crossword puzzles.

There=E2=80=99s another way in which this pricing is symbolic, though: auto=
-regressive LLMs already make a lot of sense as an assistant (=E2=80=9Chelp=
 me write this letter=E2=80=9D); the promise of something like o1 is that i=
t actually can function as an agent, with the ability to do work =E2=80=94 =
work that has been done before, to be clear =E2=80=94 without the in-depth =
level of supervision required by LLMs. That=E2=80=99s worth a lot more mone=
y!

Here is the challenge with ChatGPT specifically: a chat app =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
even one that comes packaged in a great app =E2=80=94 is much more like an =
assistant than an agent. Yes, you can give o1 something to solve, do someth=
ing else, and it will send you a notification when it=E2=80=99s done, but t=
here is a lot more scaffolding necessary to build an agent. Which is fine: =
that $200/month price would actually be much too low if it were trivial to =
leverage o1 autonomously, but at the same time, it=E2=80=99s not clear how =
many use cases require a slow and expensive thinking assistant instead of a=
 cheap and fast one whose first answer is good enough.

In short, I remain optimistic about o1 and scaling compute at inference tim=
e; I do question the extent to which ChatGPT will end up being the best way=
 to fully leverage its capabilities, but that=E2=80=99s fine: that=E2=80=99=
s why the Plus level exists, and is priced competitively with alternatives =
like Claude.

Sora
----

Yesterday=E2=80=99s big announcement is that Sora, OpenAI=E2=80=99s video g=
eneration model, is now publicly available to Plus and Pro users. From Open=
AI=E2=80=99s post ( https://openai.com/index/sora-is-here/ ) :

Our video generation model is rolling out at sora.com ( https://sora.com/ )=
.

Earlier this year, we introduced Sor, our model that can create realistic v=
ideos from text, and shared our initial research progress=E2=81=A0 on world=
 simulation. Sora serves as a foundation for AI that understands and simula=
tes reality=E2=80=94an important step towards developing models that can in=
teract with the physical world.

We developed a new version of Sora =E2=80=94 Sora Turbo =E2=80=94 that is s=
ignificantly faster than the model we previewed in February. We=E2=80=99re =
releasing it today as a standalone product at Sora.com to ChatGPT Plus and =
Pro users.

I didn=E2=80=99t actually get to try Sora, because they turned off new acco=
unt creation due to overwhelming demand; I did enjoy MKBHD=E2=80=99s YouTub=
e review ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DOY2x0TyKzIQ ). There are three=
 things that stood out to me:

* First, the amount of work that went into the Sora interface seems very im=
pressive to me. This is another example of OpenAI=E2=80=99s product capabil=
ities, which seem far ahead of any of their competitors.
* Second, here we are, two days after the announcement of ChatGPT Pro, with=
 a new justification for that higher price: more videos (500 per month vers=
us 50) and at higher resolution (up to 1080p versus up to 720p). That=E2=80=
=99s a pretty big delta!
* Third, MKBHD=E2=80=99s number one complaint was weak object permanence ( =
https://youtu.be/OY2x0TyKzIQ?si=3D8uCoZLNI9Jg42KPG&t=3D386 ). Sora just sor=
t of forgets where certain objects are, like legs, or a smartphone in a tec=
h reviewer=E2=80=99s hand that appears and disappears.

This last one ties back into the o1 discussion above. What I get from these=
 videos is the sense that the current version of Sora is a bit like regular=
 LLMs, in that it seems to generate its best attempt at a video in a single=
 shot; in this case the lack of object permanence is basically akin to a ha=
llucination. What likely seems necessary is a recursive approach to video g=
eneration that checks previous and following frames to make sure everything=
 makes sense, just like o1 uses chain of thought to revisit its proposed an=
swer and make changes until it gets it right.

In other words, what seems necessary is more inference time compute, which =
raises the question: how long until there is a ChatGPT subscription for $2,=
000/month? That might seem crazy, until you remember that you=E2=80=99re ge=
nerating video at zero marginal cost to yourself. It=E2=80=99s a tremendous=
 deal =E2=80=94 if you use it.

That=E2=80=99s the thing, though. Maybe the biggest takeaway from AI to-dat=
e is the massive returns that come from agency in terms of leveraging its c=
apability; speaking of MKBHD, I wrote in MKBHDs for Everything ( https://st=
